<h3 class="thick__padding">What is money?</h3>
 <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">       
Cash, dosh, mulah, cheese, paper, the filthy lucre, wedge, and of course the root of all evil: there are plenty of pseudonyms for money, but when asking the question "what is money", the answer is more elusive than the simplicity of the question implies.
                    <br>
                    <br>

Is it the coins in your pocket?  Is it the balance figure on your bank statement? Is the $US1.5 trillion that was created by a few keystrokes on a computer at the Federal Reserve Bank of America in 2008 to bailout the banking system?  These are all valid representations, so a proper definition must be broad enough to capture them as well as all of the other practical examples you might think of. So let's simply define money as a way of assigning an agreed value to goods and services so that they can be exchanged between people.
 <br>
<br>

You can exchange the coins in your pocket for a lollipop.  You look at your bank balance and judge whether you have enough to exchange it for a horse or car or a can of baked beans. And the officer at the Fed who placed over a trillion dollars in the bank accounts of America’s largest financial institutions was expecting that in exchange they would avoid the collapse of the world’s economy. Bargain!
                    <br>
                    <br>

There is an interesting fiction in the concept of money:  it only works if we all believe it works. In Yuval Noah Harahi’s excellent book “Sapiens” he calls the development of money a “purely mental revolution. It involved the creation of a new inter-subjective reality that exists solely in the people’s shared imagination”. In other words, if you believe a pint of Guinness can be exchanged for a €5 note and the bartender believes it as well, then sláinte, the system works!
<br>
<br>
More on this subject:  listen to this <a href="https://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/423/the-invention-of-money" target="_blank"><u>excellent podcast</u></a> from the This American Life team.
                    <br>
                    <br>
            </p>
