<h3 class="thick__padding">Enter the cryptocurrency</h3>
   <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">             
In 2008 a mysterious whitepaper appeared on The Cryptography Mailing list at metzdowd.com.  Nothing mysterious about the content of the article, but with the person (or persons) who wrote it. Its author was Satoshi Nakamoto: an unfamiliar name in a community where unfamiliarity was unusual, particularly as the titular “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System” paper seemed to arrive as a fully-formed and thoroughly tested solution for something that many in the community had tried to build before and had failed: a robust, cryptographic, trustless, decentralised electronic money system.
                    <br>
                    <br>
None of the concepts introduced in the bitcoin whitepaper were actually new: the genius was solving the problems caused by previous digital money projects just by engineering existing designs in a better way! The whitepaper outlined how transactions could be clumped into a "block", then imprinted with a time-stamped, hashed identification number and placed at the end of chain of previously created blocks, with the prior block’s id number baked into its own. This would ensure that transactions of a certain “depth” would be practically impossible to alter: so everyone could trust that the transactions were accurate and immutable (unchangeable). This along with the use of public key cryptography, which the sender uses to "lock" the value of the transaction and ensure only the correct receiver can "unlock" that value, an automated method of capped "quantitative easing" (i.e. the creation of the money supply) meant that a central bank or central clearing agency (e.g. a credit card company) was unnecessary.
<br>
<br>
And so was born bitcoin and the "blockchain" and an overnight sensation a decade in the making.  The whitepaper spawned whole new industries, billions of dollars of investment and inspired innovation in diverse and hitherto unrelated fields.  It has also, inevitably, inspired fraudsters, charlatans and hackers to steal huge amounts from naive citizens and badly designed host-applications.
                    <br>
                    <br>

Further reading: you can actually read the original whitepaper <a href="https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf" target="_blank"><u>here</u></a>
<br>
Or for an excellent overview of the history of bitcoin, watch the Netflix documentary: <a href="https://www.netflix.com/gb/title/80154500" target="_blank"><u>Banking on Bitcoin</u></a>

            </p>
