<h3 class="thick__padding">How does KPcoin Work?</h3>
 <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">
KPcoin is essentially the same as bitcoin: it uses a library attached to the core bitcoin software designed to work with Node.JS, which is language that the website is written in. This library is known as <a href="http://bcoin.io" target="_blank"><u>bcoin</u></a>.  Bcoin in turn uses the the core bitcoin software as its base - so there is a direct technical link between KPcoin and the bitcoin software. See the below for a deeper analysis of bitcoin and the key differences between bitcoin and KPcoin. In this section we'll introduce the key concepts and functions in play when you send and receive KPcoins.
        <br>
     <br>
           
<div id="pkc-primer" class="sub__menu"><b>Public Key Cryptography:</b></div>
 <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">    
 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography" target="_blank"><u>Public key cryptography</u></a> is the foundation of ownership on the bitcoin and KPcoin network. As it applies here, and in basic terms, a user of the currency has two keys: a private key and a public key. An amount of value being sent is "locked" by the sender by tagging it with the receiver's public key, and can only be "unlocked" (i.e. spent) by the person (or organisation, or computer program) who owns the private key. A public key is public and a private key should be kept...well...you guessed it: private.     
            </p>
      <br>
        <br>
            
            <div id="transaction-wallet-primer" class="sub__menu"><b>Transactions and Wallets:</b></div>
             <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">         
The most important part of the bitcoin protocol is the transaction (commonly abbreviated to "TX"): they track and store the value of currency that belongs to the private key's owner, they are the basis of blocks in the blockchain and they are the method to which a "miner" pays themselves a reward for securing the network. If there are no transactions flowing, then the network effects don't occur and the system seizes up - the are the lifeblood of cryptocurrencies.
        <br>
        <br>
In their most basic form, transactions are simply references to inputs and outputs: the amount of KPcoin owned, aka the balance, is simply the total of amount of unspent outputs that can be unlocked using your private key/s. In order to buy something you must form a transaction that has a sufficiently large input as to cover the cost (and transaction fees), with any "change" being paid back to you as a new output.  See below diagram and explanation from the original whitepaper:
        <br>
        <br>

             <div class="splash__no-background-no-top-margin copy__block-center-medium-large"><img style="max-width:95%" src="img/tx-ov.png"> 
            </div> 

                 <br>
                 <br>
                 
   <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">               
In order to send or receive cryptocurrency you need to have an application called a "wallet".  These can be thought of the digital equivalent of a real-world wallet (or purse), but this is only really for convenience - most wallet applications can and do perform many more tasks. The odd thing about a cryptocurrency wallet is that it's just an abstraction of your private key: you can have as many wallets as you want, but the amount of money you own is still linked to your private key. If you set up 10 different wallets with the same private key you don't get 10x your balance! Conversely you can have one wallet with many private keys, so when it comes to your balance, all the wallet is doing is providing a link between your key/s and your transaction history.
                    
<br>
    <br> 
When receiving money, the sender will simply tag the output of the transaction with your public key so that only the person who has access to the associated private key can spend it. That is what counts as ownership. When sending money, or making a purchase you will have to find a transaction (or multiple transactions) that add up to more than than the purchase price, tag it with the recipient's public key and "unlock" the previous transaction/s with your private key (to prove you have the right to spend it). Luckily a wallet will scan your available unspent outputs and form a transaction in accordance with the rules of the protocol: you don't have to do any clever programming, the wallet does it all for you!
<br>
    <br>
 
You could build your own wallet software, but in order to successfully transact you'd have to make sure it can construct transactions properly. If you are using bitcoin it is far easier (and safer) just to download a reputable wallet - the bitcoin.org website is a great resource and gives a breakdown of currently available <a href="https://bitcoin.org/en/choose-your-wallet" target="_blank"><u>wallet software</u></a>. 
<br> 
        <br> 
KPcoin comes with a web wallet hosted on the website for you - in fact that's the only type of wallet you can use with KPcoin as it is a closed system (see the differences between bitcoin and KPcoin below).  This is normally not recommended as it means your private key is stored on someone else's system. On the plus side it means that you don't have to worry about losing your private key - as the website will (should!) keep a backup, but it does mean you have to trust that they will keep your data private. On the personal side you can have a wallet on your phone, on a USB stick, a piece of paper or even in your brain (by memorising a pass phrase). Although technically the last two are just examples of storing your private key offline: in order to transact you will still need some sort of wallet software connected to the network.  With a personal wallet the safekeeping of your private key is entirely your responsibility.
