    <div id="nodes-and-miners" class="sub__menu"><b>Nodes, Miners and Proof of Work:</b></div>
             <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">    
                 
A "full node" is a computer that runs a full version of the bitcoin or KPcoin protocol, keeps a copy of the history of all transactions and connects to other nodes in the network to inform them of transactions and validate other node's blocks. 
      <br>
    <br>                
"Miners", who are sometimes, and more accurately referred to as "bookkeepers", usually run a full node as they need the most comprehensive and up-to-date version of the transaction history so the can build new unconfirmed transactions into blocks. After assembling a candidate block, the miner enters a race with other miners to find a number lower than than that of the network's target. This target is acquired through repeated attempts at hashing the block's header (which includes the previous block's hash number), which produces a random number and by adding and iterating a variable number (called a nonce) trillions of times a second, new attempts at reaching the target are made. They repeat until they're lucky enough to get under the target, or if they get notification from another miner that they've been successful (at which point they give up on this race, and move on to the next). If they win the race they announce it to all other miners, who validate the result. The miner can now include a special transaction (called a coinbase transaction) in the winning block where they reward themselves with bitcoin or KPcoin (essentially creating money), and finally the block is then placed at the tip of the blockchain.  The randomness of the target number means the miners have to do work to find it, and since it is performed according to the rules of the network and is validated by the other miners, it can be proved.  This is why it is called "Proof-of-Work".  Press the button below to watch an animation of this process:
