 <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font">  
Since the winning hash id includes the previous block's hash id, blocks can only ever be in sequence. Given the difficulty and work that goes into finding the target number, the sequence is (almost) impossible to break or forge. If two miners happen to find hash number at the same time, then there'll temporarily be a fork in the chain. However whoever wins the next block will choose the spur of the fork that they will build on (by choosing one of the forked block's hash number to include in their candidate block header) and the other block will be orphaned.  Any non-duplicated transactions from this orphaned block go back into the unconfirmed transaction pot and will be picked up again in the next round. 
      
