<h3 class="thick__padding">Who Controls Bitcoin?</h3>
     <p class="copy__block-left-medium-large black__font"> 
If you've read all of the "Discover More" section you'll have a good grasp of the mechanics of cryptocurrencies as it applies to bitcoin and its brethren. In summary there are four main elements: the software - known as the bitcoin protocol.  The blockchain - which is the public ledger which the network uses to log all transactions. The consensus rules - the way which independent members of the network agree on the validity of transactions and issuance of coins and the Proof-of-Work algorithm - a way of ensuring the integrity of the blockchain.
                     <br>
                    <br>
The bitcoin protocol was defined initially by Satoshi Nakamoto in the original bitcoin whitepaper, but the ongoing stewardship is performed by group of volunteers.  It is an open-source software hosted on <a href="https://github.com/bitcoin" target="_blank"><u>GitHub </u></a> which means anyone can download the software and play with it, but the master version is controlled by a core development team. Anyone can suggest changes, which are vetted by the core team and if the changes are "sensible" they are proposed to the network as Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIPS). "The network" in the case is everybody who uses bitcoin, but to think that this is a completely egalitarian situation where everyone has the same amount of influence is euphemistic: those companies who run big exchanges or mining pools have more of a say in the implementation of any BIPS.   
<br><br>
                    
As with most human endeavours that involve large groups, there are differences of opinion. Probably the most famous example is the problem of the block size on the bitcoin blockchain, where lines are drawn between those who believe a larger block size is essential for speeding up transaction confirmations, and those who reject it on the grounds that this would cause extra storage costs and goes against some of the core principals that Satoshi outlined in her whitepaper. There have already been two bitcoin-based cryptocurrencies with their own blockchains (bitgold and bitcash) that have gone off on their own "forks" to solve the dispute, but in BIP141 - "Segregated Witness" there has been a proposal to change the native bitcoin blockchain to allow a larger block size, and separate out the digital signature part of the transaction to free up even more space. The core developers eventually decided not to implement this change, as the risk an unreconcilable fork in the blockchain which would have had damaged the reputation of the protocol, but which means bitcoin in it's current state will not have the same speed of transaction as traditional payment platforms, and newer, more nimble cryptocurrencies.
 <br>
<br>
To learn more about the current governance of Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies, and for suggestions on how this might be shaped in the future, the World Economic Forum produced a comprehensive whitepaper called <a href="http://www3.weforum.org/docs/WEF_Realizing_Potential_Blockchain.pdf" target="_blank"><u>Realizing the Potential of Blockchain</u></a>.
<br>
<br>
To learn more about some of the wrangling that has been taking place over block size <a href="https://www.coindesk.com/understanding-segwit2x-bitcoins-next-fork-might-different/" target="_blank"><u>click here</u></a>.
<br>
<br>
The bitcoin software is, in comparison to most widespread applications, very simple: this is deliberate to make it more resistant to hacking. In fact some of the architecture date back to the 1970s, and while this reduced complexity reduces the number of possible applications that can be built on the system, it increases its robustness. The major "competitor" to bitcoin is called "Ethereum" and it allows entire software applications to be built on its blockchain by anyone, which gives it much more flexibility, but introduces many more points of attack by malicious actors.  Given that bitcoin is a store of value (and for some lucky early adopters, quite a large store!), compulsorily peer-to-peer, open to all, its resistance to attack is of huge importance.
